There are two methods you could use, both of which you have mentioned already.

The first is to parse against an arbitrary test date-time. This has been covered by GSerg&#39;s answer, but in brief, you essentially create a dummy date, then parse it to string and back using your format string. Obviously your test time should have a time other than 00:00, otherwise you still won&#39;t be able to tell; and it should also have a date other than &quot;today&quot; or &quot;January 1, 0001&quot; (see [Documentation][1]).

The second option is to check against the full set of date-time format string variables (see [Documentation][2]) - so, something like this (although it&#39;s subject to change in future implementations of the .NET framework):

The Date-related items are the following:

&gt; &quot;d&quot; &quot;dd&quot; &quot;ddd&quot; &quot;dddd&quot; &quot;g&quot; &quot;gg&quot; &quot;M&quot; &quot;MM&quot; &quot;MMM&quot; &quot;MMMM&quot; &quot;y&quot; &quot;yy&quot; &quot;yyy&quot;
&gt; &quot;yyyy&quot; &quot;yyyyy&quot; &quot;/&quot;

The Time-related items are the following:

&gt; &quot;f&quot; &quot;ff&quot; &quot;fff&quot; &quot;ffff&quot; &quot;fffff&quot; &quot;ffffff&quot; &quot;fffffff&quot; &quot;F&quot; &quot;FF&quot; &quot;FFF&quot; &quot;FFFF&quot;
&gt; &quot;FFFFF&quot; &quot;FFFFFF&quot; &quot;FFFFFFF&quot; &quot;h&quot; &quot;hh&quot; &quot;H&quot; &quot;HH&quot; &quot;s&quot; &quot;ss&quot; &quot;t&quot; &quot;tt&quot; &quot;m&quot;
&gt; &quot;mm&quot; &quot;:&quot;

The following are ambiguous, could be either - so we&#39;ll ignore these:

&gt; &quot;K&quot; &quot;z&quot; &quot;zz&quot; &quot;zzz&quot;

this gives us the following pseudo-code:

    If date1 contains any of (d,g,M,y,/) then date = true
